The AUV MBES WCI data captured the plume’s lower part (< 5 m) during a total time of 3.5 h (19 April 2021; from 08:40 to 12:05) on the first day of the mining trial (1st strip, Fig. 3 and Fig. 5). The recorded data showed a variable spatial extent while the plume was spreading over a maximum distance of ≈ 700 m, which was recorded continuously for the last two hours (Fig. 5). The 2 MHz ADCP at NIOZ_PFM-04 showed that the average current direction and magnitude at 2.25 m altitude when the plume was passing by, was 117° and 0.062 m s−1 respectively. According to the OBS data at NIOZ_PFM-04 and RBNIS_PFM-01, the average concentration was 18.37 mg L−1 at 1 m altitude. The cross-sectional area defined by the MBES WCI maximum spatial extent along the AUV flight path was nearly normal to the plume axis (defined by the average current direction) with a 22° deviation from this. It has a length of 640 m, a height of 5 m and a 95° angle between its normal vector and the N (Supplementary Fig. S18). We assumed a constant concentration, current direction and magnitude (equal to the above values) for the entire cross-sectional area of the first two metres of altitude during the two hours with the maximum recorded plume spread. The altitude of 2 m is based on previous work2, which showed that 92 to 98% of the sediment mass remains below 2 m. The nodule collector average flow rate was also assumed constant for these two hours (12 kg s−1)20. The equations used for estimating the sediment transport are as follows:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
